Part 0: Context¶

I initially made this presentation for a PyData presentation and have since expanded it. It was made with a technical audience with the following priorities in mind:

Highest Priority:¶

  • Good model
  • Clean code
  • Tests for complicated methods or classes

Lower Priority:¶

  • Efficiency
  • Full test coverage

Part 1: sklearn pipelines and pandas

sklearn pipelines¶

  • Way to string together different steps in the cleaning and modeling process
  • Simple Interface: All steps must implement fit and transform

fit¶

  • sets any variables related to the transform derived from training data
  • inputs: training data and target
  • output: self

transform¶

  • applies a transformation to incoming data
  • inputs: array-like data
  • output: transformed array-like data

Simple Example¶

Transformation that subsets Dataframe to only the columns listed in subcols

class SubsetData(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self,subcols):
        self.subcols = subcols

    def transform(self, X, **transform_params):
        return X[self.subcols]

    def fit(self, X, y=None, **fit_params):
        return self

BaseEstimator¶

This class implements get_params and set_params, which keeps track of parameters associated with the model. This comes in handy when using functionality like GridSearchCV

TransformerMixin¶

Implements fit_transform so fit and transform only need to be defined once

Complex Example¶

Transformation that normalizes numeric data so it has mean zero and variance 1

class Normalize(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def fit(self, X, *args, **kwargs):
        mean_var_dict = {}
        for col in X.columns:
            inarray = X[col]
            mean = np.mean(inarray.values)
            var = np.var(inarray.values)
            mean_var_dict[col]={'mean':mean,"var":var}
        self.mean_var_dict=mean_var_dict
        return self

    def normalize(self, inseries):
        colname = inseries.name
        mean = self.mean_var_dict[colname]['mean']
        var = self.mean_var_dict[colname]['var']
        if var>0:
            normed = (inseries.values-mean)/var
        else:
            normed = inseries.values
        return normed

    def transform(self, X, *args, **kwargs):
        return X.apply(self.normalize, axis=0)

 
 
 

Building a Pipeline¶

Multiple Transformations can be strung together into a pipeline

numeric_cleaning = Pipeline([
        ('subset',SubsetData(numeric+numeric_categorical)),
        ('impute',PandizedTransform(SimpleImputer())),
        ('cap',CapPercentile(upper_percent=99, lower_percent=1)),
        ('norm',Normalize())])

Feature generated from distince pipelines can be brought together using FeatureUnion

External Modeling Libraries¶

class ModelTransformer(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    '''
    Inspired by: http://zacstewart.com/2014/08/05/pipelines-of-featureunions-of-pipelines.html
    '''
    def __init__(self, model, modelname=None):
        self.model = model
        self.modelname = modelname
        self.columns = []

    def fit(self, X, *args, **kwargs):
        self.model.fit(X, *args, **kwargs)
        try:
            self.columns = list(X.columns)
        except AttributeError:
            self.columns = []
        return self

    def transform(self, X, **transform_params):
        if self.modelname is not None:
            outdf = pd.DataFrame(data={self.modelname: self.model.predict(X)},
                                 index=X.index)
        elif isinstance(X, pd.DataFrame) or isinstance(X, pd.Series):
            outdf = pd.Series(data=self.model.predict(X),
                              index=X.index)
        else:
            outdf = pd.DataFrame(self.model.predict(X))
        return outdf

    def predict(self, X):
        return self.model.predict(X)

 
 
 

Are we ready to start modeling?¶

pandas and sklearn do not always get along¶

  • sklearn started allowing pandas dataframes as inputs with version 0.15 in 2014, most often by extracting the underlying 2-D Numpy Array
  • This will break your pipelines if a transformation expects a dataframe and gets a numpy array

Example: One-Hot Encoding¶

  • Pandas has a one-hot encoder, but it isn't stateful so it can't easily be wrapped to be a transformation
  • sklearn has a one-hot encoder, but it isn't built to work with dataframes

Solution: Build a Pandas-Friendly One-Hot Encoder!¶

class PandasOHE(BaseEstimator,TransformerMixin):
    def fit(self, X, *args, **kwargs):
        new_columns_dict = {}
        left_out_dict = {}
        for col in X.columns:
            inarray = X[col]
            counted = Counter(inarray)
            left_out = counted.most_common()[0][0]
            left_out_dict[col]=left_out
            new_column_mapping = {}
            for value in counted.keys():
                if value == left_out:
                    continue
                new_column_mapping[value]="{}_{}".format(col, str(value))
            new_columns_dict[col] = new_column_mapping     
        self.new_columns_dict = new_columns_dict
        self.left_out_dict = left_out_dict
        return self

    def transform(self, X, *args, **transform_params):
        array_of_dfs = []
        for col in X.columns:
            inarray = X[col].values
            col_mapping = self.new_columns_dict[col]
            array_of_dfs.append(pd.DataFrame(index=X.index, 
                               data = {val:(key==inarray)
                                       for key,val in col_mapping.items()}))
        return pd.concat(array_of_dfs, axis=1)

 
 
 

Is it worth it?¶

Benefits¶

  • Modularizes Code
  • Makes it easy to try different combinations of features
  • Parameter-optimiation made wasy with GridCVSearch
  • Hierarchical Models are trivial

Drawbacks¶

  • Requires extra time and code
  • Requires spending time writing custom transformations for simple operations (I had to write an identity transformation at one point), especially when using pandas
  • Learning Curve

Part 2: Predicting House Prices¶

Problem:¶

Can one predict housing prices in Ames, Iowa as part of this Kaggle competition?

Data:¶

  • Data from 1,460 homes sold in Ames, Iowa between 2006 and 2010
  • 79 features describing the homes, some categorical, some numeric
  • Some missing values (for example, homes without pools have an na in 'PoolQC')

Goal: Minimize the RMS of the Logs of the Predicted and Actual¶

Partitioning the Features¶

numeric: ${\rm I\!R}$-valued
numeric_categorical: $\mathbb{W}$-valued
ordered_categorical: Categories with an inheret ordering, "ExterCond" where categories are
        Ex : Excellent
        Gd : Good
        TA : Average/Typical
        Fa : Fair
        Po : Poor
unordered_categorical: Categories with no inheret ordering, like neighborhood

class AssignOrdinals(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self):
        self.replace_missing_with = -1

    def get_level_mapping(self, column_data, y):
        grouped_target = defaultdict(list)
        for target_el, response_el in zip(column_data, y):
            grouped_target[target_el].append(response_el)
        ordered_keys = sorted(grouped_target.keys(), key=lambda x: np.median(grouped_target[x]))
        return {key: i for i, key in enumerate(ordered_keys)}

    def fit(self, X, y=None, **fit_params):
        self.label_dict = {colname: self.get_level_mapping(X[colname].values, y)
                           for colname in X.columns}
        self.label_values = {colname: list(mapping.values())
                             for colname, mapping in self.label_dict.items()}
        return self

    def check_series_for_missed(self, inseries):
        colname = inseries.name
        try:
            missed = np.isin(inseries.values, self.label_values[colname], invert=True)
        except TypeError:  # column has compativle type with label_values
            # use slower for loop for this case
            missed = [(el in self.label_values[colname]) for el in inseries.values]
        outseries = inseries.copy()
        outseries[missed] = -1
        return outseries

    def transform(self, X, **kwargs):
        X_replaced = X.replace(self.label_dict)
        # replace any strings that were missed due to being a rare level with -1
        X_out = X_replaced.apply(self.check_series_for_missed, axis=0)
        return X_out

# Assign numberic value to categorical data 
# by ordering by the mean and assigning integer values in order

categorical_to_numeric = Pipeline([
            ('subset',SubsetData(ordered_categorical+unordered_categorical)),
            ("assign_ordinals", AssignOrdinals())])

regression_wcat = Pipeline([
    ('features', PandasFeatureUnion([
            ("categorical", categorical_to_numeric),
            ("numeric", numeric_cleaning)])),
    ('lasso',lasso_pipeline)
        ])

              'features__numeric__initial_cleaning__cap__lower_percent':[0,5,10,15], 
              'features__numeric__initial_cleaning__cap__upper_percent':[100,95,90],

# Regression with PCA
numeric_cleaning_pca = Pipeline([
        ('subset',SubsetData(numeric+numeric_categorical)),
        ('impute',PandizedTransform(SimpleImputer())),
        ('cap',CapPercentile(upper_percent=95, lower_percent=5)),
        ('norm',Normalize())])

numeric_features_wsquare_pca = Pipeline([('initial_cleaning',numeric_cleaning_pca),
                            ('all_features',PandasFeatureUnion([
                                ('squared',square_pipeline),
                                ('same', IdentityTransformation())
                            ]))])

pca_all = Pipeline([
    ('features', PandasFeatureUnion([
            ("categorical", categorical_to_numeric),
            ("numeric", numeric_features_wsquare_pca)])),
    ('pca',PandasPCA(PCA(n_components=81))),
    ('normal',regression_pipeline)
        ])

evaluate_model(pca_all, "Regression with Cat, Square, and PCA")

In [16]:
test_array = []
train_array = []
alpha_array = range(100,2000,100)
regression_all_inloop = clone(regression_all)
for alpha in alpha_array:
    regression_all_inloop.set_params(lasso__model__model__alpha=alpha)
    train_pred = regression_all_inloop.fit_transform(train, train['SalePrice'])
    train_metric = compute_metric(train_pred, train['SalePrice'])
    test_pred = regression_all_inloop.transform(test)
    test_metric = compute_metric(test_pred, test['SalePrice'])
    test_array.append(test_metric)
    train_array.append(train_metric)
plt.plot(alpha_array,train_array,'-o',label="train")
plt.plot(alpha_array,test_array,'-o',label="test")
plt.legend()
plt.title("Effect of Alpha on Lasso")
plt.xlabel("Alpha")
plt.ylabel("Error")
plt.show()

Using Decision Trees to Engineer Features¶

I noticed some points with very high residuals that appeared to have some traits in common. I built a decision tree fit on high-residual points to help engineer features to better predict them

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier, export_graphviz
test_features = pipeline_features.transform(test)
dtree = DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight = {1:len(test)/13, 0:1}, max_leaf_nodes=5)
dtree.fit(test_features, residuals<-50000)
export_graphviz(dtree, out_file="images/tree1.png", feature_names = test_features.columns)

dtree.fit(test_features, residuals<-50000)
export_graphviz(dtree, out_file="images/tree2.png", feature_names = test_features.columns)

bighouse_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('subset', SubsetData(['GrLivArea','LotArea'])),
    ('threshold', StrictlyGreaterThan({'GrLivArea':1930.5, 'LotArea':12350.5})),
    ('and', MultiplyColumns(['GrLivArea','LotArea'], 'bighouse', replace=True))
])

bigbasement_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('subset', SubsetData(['TotalBsmtSF','2ndFlrSF'])),
    ('threshold', StrictlyGreaterThan({'TotalBsmtSF':1644., '2ndFlrSF':892.})),
    ('and', MultiplyColumns(['TotalBsmtSF',  '2ndFlrSF'], 'bigbasement', replace=True))
])

pipeline_xgboost_bighouse = Pipeline([
        ('features',PandasFeatureUnion([
            ('original_features',Pipeline([
                ('features',pipeline_features_xgb),
                ('reduceFeatures',SubsetData(ordered_cols[:138], safe=True))])),
            ('bighouse_pipeline',bighouse_pipeline),
            ('bigbasement_pipeline',bigbasement_pipeline)])),
        ('fittree',xgboost_lasso_sub)
])

evaluate_model(pipeline_xgboost_bighouse, "GBM with Lasso, feature selection, bighouse")
